Setup

Load packages.

library("ggplot2")
library("ChIPQC")
library("DiffBind")

Load annotation file.

anno <- read.table("../../data/yeast/annotation.txt", sep = "\t",

Prepare sample sheet for ChIPQC and DiffBind.

# SampleID: Identifier string for sample
SampleID <- anno$sample[1:4]
# Factor: Identifier string for factor
Factor <- anno$set1[1:4]
# Replicate: Replicate number of sample
Replicate <- substr(anno$replicate[1:4], 2, 2)
Replicate <- as.numeric(Replicate)
# bamReads: file path for bam file containing aligned reads for ChIP sample
bamReads <- list.files(path = "../../data/yeast/bam",
                       pattern = glob2rx("H3K4ME3*sorted.rmdup.bam"),
                       full.names = TRUE)
# bamControl: file path for bam file containing aligned reads for control sample
bamControl <- list.files(path = "../../data/yeast/bam",
                       pattern = glob2rx("Input*sorted.rmdup.bam"),
                       full.names = TRUE)
# Had to reverse order because naming scheme of input files is different
# from the IP files.
bamControl <- rep(rev(bamControl), each = 2)
# ControlID: Identifier string for control sample
ControlID <- rep(anno$sample[6:5], each = 2)
# Peaks: path for file containing peaks for sample. format determined by PeakCaller field or caller parameter
Peaks <- list.files(path = "../../data/yeast/peaks",
                    pattern = glob2rx("*_peaks.xls"),
                    full.names = TRUE)
# PeakCaller: Identifier string for peak caller used. If Peaks is not a bed file, this will determine how the Peaks file is parsed. macs: MACS .xls file
PeakCaller <- "macs"
samplesheet <- data.frame(SampleID, Factor, Replicate, bamReads, bamControl,
                          ControlID, Peaks, PeakCaller, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

All the samples have a high fraction of reads in peaks (frip), though the full length Set1 samples tend to have a higher fraction.

plotFrip(qc)
## Using Sample as id variables

The summit of the peaks are enriched for signal. Though this also highlights the difference between the truncated Set1 replicates.

plotPeakProfile(qc)

Lastly, all the samples have a cross correlation greater than 1, indicating enrichment. Strangely, the cross correlation does not appear normally distributed as normal. This may be related to why I had to decrease the lower threshold from 5 to 3 when trying to find paired peaks. Maybe I could try specifying --no-model --shiftsize=147 to be the size of one nucleosome.

plotCC(qc)

Test for differential H3K4me3

Contruct dba object.

d <- dba(sampleSheet = samplesheet,
         minOverlap = 2, # Peaks have to be identified in at least
                         # 2 of the 4 samples
         # Lots of configuration options. I only comment when I change
         # the default setting.
         config = data.frame(RunParallel = TRUE,
                             reportInit = "DBA",
                             DataType = DBA_DATA_FRAME, # Return df instead of granges
                             AnalysisMethod = DBA_EDGER,
                             minQCth = 10, # Use min read qual of 10 instead of 15
                             fragmentSize = 125,
                             bCorPlot = FALSE, # Don't plot automatically
                             th = .1,
                             bUsePval=FALSE),
         bCorPlot = FALSE)
## H3K4me3.aa762_1080.r1  aa762_1080   1 macs
## H3K4me3.aa762_1080.r2  aa762_1080   2 macs
## H3K4me3.full_length.r1  full_length   1 macs
## H3K4me3.full_length.r2  full_length   2 macs

Because there are only 4 samples total, the minimum requirement that a peak is observed in at least two samples seems overly stringent. dba.overlap displays the number of peaks found in at least one sample, two samples, etc.

overlap <- dba.overlap(d, mode = DBA_OLAP_RATE)
overlap
## [1] 4038 3560 2837 2249

By requiring a peak is observed in at least two samples, I lose 478 peaks. I redefine the dba requiring a peak is only observed in one sample.

d <- dba(sampleSheet = samplesheet,
         minOverlap = 1, # Peaks have to be identified in at least
                         # 1 of the 4 samples
         # Lots of configuration options. I only comment when I change
         # the default setting.
         config = data.frame(RunParallel = TRUE,
                             reportInit = "DBA",
                             DataType = DBA_DATA_FRAME, # Return df instead of granges
                             AnalysisMethod = DBA_EDGER,
                             minQCth = 10, # Use min read qual of 10 instead of 15
                             fragmentSize = 125,
                             bCorPlot = FALSE, # Don't plot automatically
                             th = .1,
                             bUsePval=FALSE),
         bCorPlot = FALSE)
## H3K4me3.aa762_1080.r1  aa762_1080   1 macs
## H3K4me3.aa762_1080.r2  aa762_1080   2 macs
## H3K4me3.full_length.r1  full_length   1 macs
## H3K4me3.full_length.r2  full_length   2 macs

Visualize the relationship between the samples using the concordance in binding sites.

dba.plotHeatmap(d)

dba.plotPCA(d, label = DBA_REPLICATE)

Clearly the full length and truncated Set1 samples are more closely related to their replicates than each other. The first PC is the split between the two. However, it is clear in the second PC that there is substantial difference between replicates.

Now I count the reads in each peak and again compare the samples using this more quantitative measurement.

d = dba.count(d)
dba.plotHeatmap(d)

dba.plotPCA(d, label = DBA_REPLICATE)

Now the split in PC1 between the two Set1 versions is even stronger. Also, the replicates for the full length now cluster much closer together on PC2, and the truncated Set1 replicates are even further apart.

Perform the differential expression using edgeR.

d = dba.contrast(d, categories = DBA_FACTOR, minMembers = 2)
d = dba.analyze(d)
results = dba.report(d)

There are 191 regions with diffential H3K4me3 reads between the two Set1 proteins. Of these, 186 of the regions have more H3K4me3 reads in the yeast samples with the fully functional Set1. This can be visualized with the MA plots below. The red dots are significantly different regions.

dba.plotMA(d)

dba.plotMA(d, bXY = TRUE)
